TY  - JOUR
T1  - An Evaluation of Federal Policy Instruments to Stimulate Basic Research in Industry
AU  - Joglekar, Prafulla
AU  - Hamburg, Morris
Y1  - 1983/09/01
PY  - 1983
DA  - 1983/09/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.29.9.997
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.29.9.997
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 997
EP  - 1015
VL  - 29
IS  - 9
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - A model of the resource allocation behavior of a group of firms demonstrates that unaided industry allocation to basic (inappropriable) research is suboptimal. Furthermore, provision of seed money is generally counterproductive, while the provision of a matching subsidy is not very cost-efficient in increasing the allocation. Innovative policy alternatives are proposed.
AB  - A model of the resource allocation behavior of a group of firms demonstrates that unaided industry allocation to basic (inappropriable) research is suboptimal. Furthermore, provision of seed money is generally counterproductive, while the provision of a matching subsidy is not very cost-efficient in increasing the allocation. Innovative policy alternatives are proposed.
